1S Pass 2C Pass 2H Pass 3D =1= Pass 3NT Pass Pass Pass
[Note "1:4th suit"]
{North opens 1\S- how do you respond?
With 13 points, you respond 2\C, a natural 2/1 force to game.
North next bids 2\H, showing the other Major suit.  What do you rebid now?
You assume North to be 5-4 in the Majors, so you cannot support either.  You cannot bid 2NT without a stopper in \Ds. So you bid the fourth suit, 3\D, telling North you knows you must make a bid, but can't find anything appropriate.  This is an artificial bid, and normally denies a diamond stopper (otherwise you would have bid 2NT).
North rebids 3NT - what do you do now?

North now must find a bid. His choices include rebidding the 5-card \Ss, supporting South's \Cs with a doubleton Queen, or bidding 3NT with the \D K 6 as a stopper. He chooses this last option. It appears that 3NT is the best game for these two hands.}

